{
  "text": "Then, our color similarity function uses the color standard deviation calculated from the pixel sample to adapt the level of color scattering in the comparisons [CITATION_1] . The result of a particular similarity function calculation for every pixel and the color centroid (meaning the similarity measure between the pixel and the color representative value) generates the CSI. The generation of this image is the basis of our method and preserves the information of the color selected from the original color image. This CSI is a digital representation of a continuous function \u2208[0 -1] extended to the range of [0 -255] which can also be viewed as a fuzzy variable of the membership function of every pixel related to a given selected color. In CSI is possible to appreciate not only the color after segmentation but also all the minimal variations in its tonalities when it is multiplied by the original image.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "19608139"
  },
  "bib_entries": {
    "19608139": {
      "title": "Color Image Segmentation by Means of a Similarity Function",
      "abstract": "An interactive, semiautomatic image segmentation method is presented which, unlike most of the existing methods in the published literature, processes the color information of each pixel as a unit, thus avoiding color information scattering. The process has two steps: 1) The manual selection of few sample pixels of the color to be segmented, 2) The automatic generation of the so called Color Similarity Image (CSI), which is a gray level image with all the tonalities of the selected color. The color information of every pixel is integrated by a similarity function for direct color comparisons. The color integrating technique is direct, simple, and computationally inexpensive. It is shown that the improvement in quality of our proposed segmentation technique and its quick result is significant with respect to other solutions found in the literature."
    }
  }
}